Angioedema with delayed puberty may be associated with hereditary angioedema (HAE)
Hypertension with delayed puberty, angioedema, and increased immunoglobulins raise suspicion of a kidney disease
Increased Immunoglobulins may point to specific autoimmune diseases or primary immunodeficiency diseases
Blepharospasm might be a symptom of neurological or neurodegenerative conditions
Brain tumor, vascular malformation, or other space-occupying lesions might be contributing to the symptoms
Infectious diseases such as Lyme disease or Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) can cause various symptoms including delayed puberty, blepharospasm, and elevated immunoglobulins
Certain medications or dietary deficiencies can lead to delayed puberty and other symptoms
Metabolic disorders like Cushing’s syndrome or Addison’s disease should be considered
Genetic syndromes such as Prader-Willi syndrome or Sotos syndrome could be a possibility

Angioedema, telangiectasias, gastroparesis, thrombocytopenia, thromboembolic disease, and endometriosis are symptoms of a rare autoimmune disorder known as Hughes-Stovin syndrome (HSS). HSS can potentially lead to complications such as stroke and pulmonary emboli. It is essential to seek medical attention if you experience these symptoms. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial to manage the condition and prevent further complications.
